{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Build-once artifact identity + fix the provenance hook's None-commit path\n\nRestructure the release graph so the exact wheel and sdist are built once, tested\nin a clean environment, and published byte-for-byte, and fix the Hatchling hook so\nthe wheel-from-sdist path never bakes `COMMIT = None`. (Readiness Finding 3 —\nverified VALID against `release.yml`, `test.yml:455-477`, `hatch_build.py`,\n`pyproject.toml`, `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py`.)\n\n## Why\n\nThe release artifact and the CI-tested code are products of different build paths.\nThe `build` job runs `python -m build` + `twine check` (a static metadata check)\nand uploads `dist/` with **no install or functional test** before `publish`\n(`release.yml` build→publish). The clean-install CI job installs the source tree\nwith `pip install .` (`test.yml:470`) — which builds a wheel in place with `.git`\npresent — so it never exercises the sdist→wheel path. The only smoke test of the\nreal artifact is documented as **post-publication** (`docs/releasing.md`), by which\npoint PyPI immutability means recovery is yank + republish.\n\nThe provenance hook computes the commit via `git rev-parse` (`None` outside a git\ntree) and `initialize` writes `_build_info.py` **unconditionally**\n(`hatch_build.py`), with no preservation of an existing baked value and no failure\nwhen the commit is absent. `python -m build`'s default builds an sdist first, then\nbuilds the wheel **from the extracted sdist** — which has no `.git` — so the\npublished **wheel** carries `COMMIT = None` while only the sdist keeps the real SHA.\nThe one test that asserts a non-null baked SHA builds a `WheelBuilder` directly\nagainst the checkout (`tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py:202-227`), bypassing\nthe failing path, so the defect is uncaught by every existing gate.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt the pydantic / pip build-once pattern (build once → upload one artifact →\ndownload it in a separate test job that installs with the index disabled and\nexercises the public surface → download the same artifact in the publish job and\nverify hashes before publishing, never rebuilding):\n\n- **Build once**: produce wheel + sdist in one job, record SHA-256 for each, upload\n  one named artifact bundle.\n- **Test the exact wheel**: in a fresh job with no repo checkout on `PYTHONPATH`,\n  install the wheel by filename and run concrete probes — `python -c \"import rebar\"`,\n  `rebar --help`, `rebar-mcp --help`, load every packaged JSON schema\n  (`python -c \"import importlib.resources as r, json, rebar; [json.loads(f.read_text()) for f in r.files('rebar').rglob('*.json')]\"`,\n  asserting the count is non-zero and each parses), and\n  `python -c \"from rebar import _build_info; assert _build_info.COMMIT\"` — asserting\n  the embedded build info is present and non-null.\n- **Test the exact sdist**: install from the downloaded sdist in a clean dir (no\n  `.git`, `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` unset), run the same probes, and assert the installed\n  package reports a **non-null** short SHA matching the release — this exercises the\n  hook's preserve-existing path (step 2): the sdist shipped `_build_info.py` with the\n  SHA baked during the release build, and the rebuild-from-sdist must keep it rather\n  than overwrite with `None`. (This is exactly the real end-user `pip install <sdist>`\n  path, so the test doubles as the provenance guarantee for sdist installs.)\n- **Publish the same bytes**: `publish` `needs:` both test jobs, downloads the\n  original bundle, recomputes and compares hashes against the recorded build hashes,\n  and publishes without rebuilding.\n- **Complete the F4 evidence handshake.** Finding 4 delegated the wheel/sdist digests\n  to this story: the build-once job uploads an **`evidence-artifacts`** fragment\n  (the wheel/sdist SHA-256 sums) that F4's consolidation step concatenates into\n  `release-evidence.txt`, and this story **extends the `test_release_workflow_pins.py`\n  test that Finding 4 introduces** (this story `depends_on` F4, so that file already\n  exists by the time this lands) — adding to its check (f) an assertion that the\n  `evidence-artifacts` fragment name + its wiring appear in `release.yml`.\n- **Fix the hook — a four-step precedence (env var + preserve-existing + git).**\n  `hatch_build.py`'s `initialize` resolves the commit in this order: (1)\n  `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` env var if set (the release build sets it — see below); (2)\n  else **preserve** an existing non-null `COMMIT` already in `_build_info.py` if one is\n  present; (3) else `git rev-parse --short HEAD`; (4) else `None`. Step (2) is\n  essential for **install-from-sdist**: `pip install <sdist>` rebuilds a wheel from the\n  extracted tree (re-running this hook) with no `.git` and no env var, so without\n  preserve-existing the SHA the sdist shipped would be overwritten with `None` — step\n  (2) keeps it, so a published-sdist install retains provenance too (not just the\n  release wheel). (Env-var injection alone — the earlier decision — fixes only the\n  release-built wheel; preserve-existing is what carries the sdist's baked value\n  through an install.)\n- **Canonical commit format = SHORT SHA (existing convention).** `signing.py` is\n  built around short SHAs throughout (`_gate_commit_sha` → `git rev-parse --short`;\n  `gate_code_version` / `rebar_version_step` docstrings say `<short-sha>[-dirty]`), so\n  to avoid a full-vs-short skew between the baked value and the live-git value in the\n  same `rebar-version:` manifest line, the new code conforms to short SHAs rather than\n  changing `signing.py`. The workflow sets `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` to the **short** SHA\n  (`${GITHUB_SHA::7}`, matching git's default abbreviation); the git fallback stays\n  `git rev-parse --short HEAD`; `signing.py` is unchanged. The existing provenance\n  test's `[0-9a-f]{4,}` regex still matches.\n- **Fail-fast scoped to the release context:** the hook raises (fails the build) only\n  when `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` is set but empty/unresolvable — so a developer's plain\n  `pip install .` (env var unset) still degrades gracefully to the git value and\n  never breaks.\n- **Verify env-var propagation (do not assume).** The fix depends on `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT`\n  surviving from the workflow shell through `python -m build` into the Hatchling\n  `initialize` hook when the wheel is built from the extracted sdist. (Env vars\n  propagate to the build backend subprocess via inherited `os.environ` **regardless of\n  PEP 517 isolation** — isolation governs build *dependencies*, not the environment —\n  so this is not coupled to F4's `--no-isolation` choice.) The plan still **proves**\n  it with a test that runs `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=<short-hex> python -m build` and asserts\n  the resulting **wheel** (built from the extracted sdist) carries that exact short\n  SHA — rather than asserting propagation as settled fact.\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` — build-once + two artifact-test jobs + hash-gated\n  publish (coordinate with Findings 1 and 4, which also edit this file).\n- `.github/workflows/test.yml` — optionally add a wheel/sdist artifact probe to\n  regular CI so the defect is caught pre-release, not only in the release run.\n- `hatch_build.py` — four-step precedence: `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` env var (short SHA) →\n  preserve an existing non-null `COMMIT` in `_build_info.py` (install-from-sdist) →\n  `git rev-parse --short HEAD` → `None`; fail only when the env var is set but\n  empty/unresolvable (release-context fail-fast; unset = graceful preserve/git fallback\n  for sdist + dev installs).\n- `src/rebar/signing.py` — **in scope to confirm only** (no change expected): its\n  short-SHA `_gate_commit_sha` path already matches the chosen canonical short format,\n  so the baked value and the live-git value stay consistent in `gate_code_version()`\n  output regardless of install type.\n- `hatch_build.py` (`initialize`) — add `src/rebar/_build_info.py` to\n  `build_data['force_include']` so the generated (git-ignored) file is shipped in the\n  **sdist** as well as the wheel. (Do NOT add `artifacts=` to the sdist pyproject\n  target — Hatchling's sdist builder uses `include`/`exclude` only and silently ignores\n  `artifacts`, a wheel-only key; the hook's `force_include` works for both targets.)\n  Without this the sdist never contains the baked SHA and the preserve-existing path\n  has nothing to preserve.\n- `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py` — add coverage for the wheel-from-sdist\n  path (the currently-untested `COMMIT = None` case).\n- `docs/releasing.md` — **section ownership:** this story owns the \"Build-once\"\n  section, AND rewrites the existing **\"Post-release smoke test\"** section, which F1's\n  trigger change + this story's pre-publication artifact tests make obsolete (the\n  smoke test moves from post-publication to the pre-publish wheel/sdist test jobs).\n  (Finding 1 owns \"Release-source authorization\" + the existing tag→PyPI procedure /\n  Hard-rules sections; Finding 4 owns \"Pinning\".)\n- Out of scope: byte-for-byte reproducible builds (timestamps/backend determinism)\n  beyond the SHA-256 identity check through the pipeline.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The release builds artifacts once and uploads a single named bundle containing\n  the wheel, the sdist, and a `SHA256SUMS` file recording their digests; `publish`\n  downloads that same bundle and runs `sha256sum -c SHA256SUMS` (failing on any\n  mismatch) before publishing — no rebuild occurs in `publish`.\n- [ ] A wheel-test job installs the exact wheel by filename with no source checkout\n  on the path and runs concrete probes — `python -c \"import rebar\"`, `rebar --help`,\n  `rebar-mcp --help`, load every packaged JSON schema via `importlib.resources`\n  (count non-zero, each parses), and a non-null-`COMMIT` assert\n  (the wheel install does not re-run the hook, so it keeps its baked SHA). An\n  sdist-test job installs from the sdist in a clean dir (`REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` unset, no\n  `.git`) and also asserts a non-null `COMMIT` — proving the hook's preserve-existing\n  step keeps the sdist's shipped SHA through the rebuild rather than overwriting it\n  with `None`.\n- [ ] The shipped wheel carries a non-null **short** source commit matching the\n  release SHA — the workflow sets `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=${GITHUB_SHA::7}` before\n  `python -m build`, and a test (added to `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py`,\n  which currently only covers the direct-`WheelBuilder` path) asserts the wheel built\n  via the default sdist→wheel path contains `COMMIT` equal to that short SHA (today\n  this path yields `COMMIT = None`). The baked value and `signing.py`'s live-git\n  value share the short format, so `gate_code_version()` is consistent across install\n  types. The hook fails the build only when `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` is set but\n  unresolvable (release context); an unset env var falls back to git (dev\n  `pip install .` unaffected). **Both branches are pinned by concrete tests** in\n  `tests/unit/test_attestation_signing.py`: (a) `test_hook_fails_when_rebar_build_commit_empty`\n  runs `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT=\"\" python -m build` (env var set-but-empty) in a temp copy of the\n  tree and asserts the build exits non-zero (the release-context fail-fast); and (b)\n  `test_hook_falls_back_to_git_when_env_unset` builds with `REBAR_BUILD_COMMIT` unset in a\n  git checkout and asserts the wheel carries the `git rev-parse --short HEAD` value (graceful\n  dev fallback, no failure). These make the fail-fast/fallback contract codebase-verifiable,\n  not merely asserted in prose.\n- [ ] The build-once job uploads an `evidence-artifacts` fragment (wheel/sdist SHA-256\n  sums) consumed by F4's evidence-consolidation step, and the `test_release_workflow_pins.py`\n  test introduced by Finding 4 (available since this story `depends_on` F4) has its\n  check (f) extended to assert that fragment's name + wiring appear in `release.yml`.\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` describes the build-once → test → publish-same-bytes flow,\n  and the existing \"Post-release smoke test\" section is rewritten to reflect that the\n  smoke test now runs pre-publication (against the exact wheel/sdist) rather than\n  post-publication.\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate.\n"}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784104895441509001,"uuid":"7c51aca5-9c8d-46b9-95f0-9c5b0eb76447"}